As a technology-enabled assistant, here's an example of a high-quality testing framework in Cypress, utilizing Docker with the ability to capture screenshots and save them. 

Step 1: Setting up the Cypress project

First, create a new Cypress project, if you haven't already. You can quickly create a new project by running the following command in your terminal:

```
npx cypress create
```

Afterward, navigate to your project directory and install the required dependencies:

```bash
cd path/to/cypress_project
npm install cypress --save-dev
npm install cypress-image-snapshot --save-dev
```

Step 2: Dockerizing Cypress

To utilize Docker, we'll install `cypress/base` and ensure we're building the Cypress project inside the Docker container. Add the following Dockerfile to your Cypress project directory:

```dockerfile
FROM cypress/base:14.18.1-browsers

WORKDIR /app
COPY package*.json./

RUN npm install --registry=https://registry.npmjs.org

COPY..

RUN npm run build

CMD ["npm", "run", "test"]
```

Then add the following script to your `package.json`:

```json
{
  "scripts": {
    "build": "cypress run --spec 'cypress/e2e/**/*.spec.js' --spec-pattern '**/*.{spec.js,.cy.js}'",
    "test": "docker run -e CYPRESS_BASE_URL=<YOUR_BASE_URL> -v ${PWD}:/app -w /app cypress/cypress:base bash -c 'npm run build && npm run test:e2e'"
  }
}
```

Step 3: Installing Cypress Image Snapshot

Cypress Image Snapshot is a Cypress plugin that captures screenshots during your Cypress tests and compares them against a reference image. Install it with the command:

```bash
npm install cypress-image-snapshot --save-dev
```

Make sure you update your `cypress.config.js` file by adding the "imageSnapshot" plugin, like this:

```javascript
const { defineConfig } = require("cypress");
const imageSnapshot = require("cypress-image-snapshot/plugin");

export default defineConfig({
  e2e: {
    setupNodeEvents(on, config) {
      on("plugin:imageSnapshot", () => imageSnapshot(on, config));
      return config;
    },
    baseUrl: "<YOUR_BASE_URL>",
    viewportHeight: 1080,
    viewportWidth: 1920,
    specPattern: "**/*.spec.js",
    env: {
      screenshotsFolder: "cypress/screenshots",
      videosFolder: "cypress/videos",
    },
  },
});
```

Where `<YOUR_BASE_URL>` is the base URL of your application.

Step 4: Writing Cypress Tests

Finally, create a sample `cypress/e2e/specs/my-first-test.spec.js` file to test your application. It's essential to test that screenshots are being saved correctly. Here's an example:

```javascript
require("cypress/image-snapshot/index");

it("Homepage should display correctly", () => {
  cy.visit("/");
  cy.get("body").should("contain.text", "Homepage Title");
  cy.saveSnapshot("homepage");
});

it("Login page should display correctly", () => {
  cy.visit("/login");
  cy.get("form input:first").type("username");
  cy.get("form input:last").type("password");
  cy.get("form").submit();
  cy.saveSnapshot("login");
});
```

As you can see, we've added the `saveSnapshot` command from the "cypress-image-snapshot" plugin, which saves the captured screenshot with a specified filename.

That's it! You've now got a robust Cypress testing framework utilizing Docker and Cypress's ability to capture screenshots and save them, ready to test your application with confidence!

