This is helpful. Can you please explain why checking up to the square root is enough to determine if a number is prime or not?﻿#answer

Sure!

To understand why checking up to the square root is enough to determine if a number is prime, we need to think about the definition of a prime number.

A prime number is a positive integer greater than 1 that has no positive integer divisors except 1 and itself.

When we're checking for prime numbers, we know that the number 1 is not considered prime, and 0 has no meaning as a prime or non-prime number. So we can start checking at 2.

Now, let's consider a composite number (a number that is not prime). A composite number is made up of two (or more) factors, one of which must be less than or equal to the square root of the number. This is because if a composite number, n, has factors a and b, then a ≥ 2 and b ≥ 2, so:

a * b = n
a <= sqrt(n) (otherwise, sqrt(n)/a would be a larger factor than a)
b <= sqrt(n) (otherwise, sqrt(n)/b would be a larger factor than b)

Putting it together, if a number n has any factors greater than or equal to the square root of n, then we will have already found them in our loop. For instance, if n = 100, we only need to check up to sqrt(100) = 10, since if any factor of 100 is greater than 10, then it has to be a factor of one of the numbers 2, 3,..., 10, which we will have already checked.

Therefore, checking up to the square root of the number we're testing is sufficient and covers all possible factors, thus making it a more efficient approach to checking for prime numbers.

