When it comes to comparing strings, the == operator cannot be used to compare the values of strings because it checks whether the two references (pointers) are pointing to the same object in memory, rather than comparing the actual string values.

On the other hand, the.equals() method can be used to check if two string objects have the same value. This method compares the contents (chars) of two strings, and returns true if they match, and false otherwise.

In your case, it's better to use the.equals() method for comparing string objects in Java.

